# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: babylonjs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] 3D computer graphics, contrary to what the name suggests, are most often displayed on two-dimensional displays.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Unlike 3D film and similar techniques, the result is two-dimensional, without visual depth.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] More often, 3D graphics are being displayed on 3D displays, like in virtual reality systems.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] 3D graphics stand in contrast to 2D computer graphics which typically use completely different methods and formats for creation and rendering.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] 3D computer graphics rely on many of the same algorithms as 2D computer vector graphics in the wire-frame model and 2D computer raster graphics in the final rendered display.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] In computer graphics software, 2D applications may use 3D techniques to achieve effects such as lighting, and similarly, 3D may use some 2D rendering techniques.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] The objects in 3D computer graphics are often referred to as 3D models.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Unlike the rendered image, a model's data is contained within a graphical data file.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] A 3D model is a mathematical representation of *any* three-dimensional object; a model is not technically a *graphic* until it is displayed.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] A model can be displayed visually as a two-dimensional image through a process called 3D rendering, or it can be used in non-graphical computer simulations and calculations.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] With 3D printing, models are rendered into an actual 3D physical representation of themselves, with some limitations as to how accurately the physical model can match the virtual model.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] William Fetter was credited with coining the term *computer graphics* in 1961 to describe his work at Boeing.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] An early example of interactive 3-D computer graphics was explored in 1963 by the Sketchpad program at Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Lincoln Laboratory.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] One of the first displays of computer animation was *Futureworld* (1976), which included an animation of a human face and a hand that had originally appeared in the 1972 experimental short *A Computer Animated Hand*, created by University of Utah students Edwin Catmull and Fred Parke.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D computer graphics software began appearing for home computers in the late 1970s.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] The earliest known example is *3D Art Graphics*, a set of 3-D computer graphics effects, written by Kazumasa Mitazawa and released in June 1978 for the Apple II.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Virtual Reality 3D is a version of 3D computer graphics.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Although the first VR headsets appeared in the late 1950s, VR did not become widely popular until the 2000s.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] In 2012 the Oculus was released and since then, the 3D VR headset world has expanded.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] The modeling describes the process of forming the shape of an object.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] The two most common sources of 3D models are those that an artist or engineer originates on a computer with a 3D modeling tool, or models scanned into a computer from real-world objects (polygonal modeling, patch modeling, and NURBS modeling are some popular tools used in 3D modeling).
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Models can also be produced procedurally or via physical simulation.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Basically, a 3D model is formed from points called vertices that define the shape and form polygons.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] A polygon is an area formed from at least three vertices (a triangle).
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] The overall integrity of the model and its suitability to use in animation depend on the structure of the polygons.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Before rendering into an image, objects must be laid out in a 3D scene.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] This defines spatial relationships between objects, including location and size.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Animation refers to the temporal description of an object (i.e., how it moves and deforms over time).
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Popular methods include keyframing, inverse kinematics, and motion-capture).
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] These techniques are often used in combination.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] As with animation, physical simulation also specifies motion.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Stop Motion has multiple categories within such as Claymation, Cutout, Silhouette, Lego, Puppets, and Pixelation.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Claymation is the use of models made of clay used for an animation.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Some examples are Clay Fighter and Clay Jam.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Lego animation is one of the more common types of stop motion.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Lego stop motion is the use of the figures themselves moving around.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Some examples of this are Lego Island and Lego Harry Potter.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Rendering converts a model into an image either by simulating light transport to get photo-realistic images, or by applying an art style as in non-photorealistic rendering.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] The two basic operations in realistic rendering are transport (how much light gets from one place to another) and scattering (how surfaces interact with light).
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] This step is usually performed using 3-D computer graphics software or a 3-D graphics API.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Altering the scene into a suitable form for rendering also involves 3D projection, which displays a three-dimensional image in two dimensions.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Materials and textures are properties that the render engine uses to render the model.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] One can give the model materials to tell the render engine how to treat light when it hits the surface.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Textures are used to give the material color using a color or albedo map, or give the surface features using a bump map or normal map.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] It can also be used to deform the model itself using a displacement map.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D computer graphics software produces computer-generated imagery (CGI) through 3D modeling and 3D rendering or produces 3-D models for analytical, scientific, entertainment, and industrial purposes.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] There are many varieties of files supporting 3-D graphics, for example, Blender (.blend), Wavefront (.obj), .fbx and .x DirectX files.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Each file type generally tends to have its own unique data structure.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Each file format can be accessed through its respective applications, such as DirectX files, and Quake.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Alternatively, files can be accessed through third-party standalone programs, or via manual decompilation.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modeling software is a class of 3-D computer graphics software used to produce 3-D models.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Individual programs of this class are called modeling applications or modelers.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modeling starts by describing 3 display models: drawing points, drawing lines and drawing triangles and other polygonal patches.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modelers allow users to create and alter models via their 3-D mesh.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Users can add, subtract, stretch and otherwise change the mesh to their desire.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Models can be viewed from a variety of angles, usually simultaneously.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Models can be rotated and the view can be zoomed in and out.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modelers can export their models to files, which can then be imported into other applications as long as the metadata are compatible.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Many modelers allow importers and exporters to be plugged-in, so they can read and write data in the native formats of other applications.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Most 3-D modelers contain a number of related features, such as ray tracers and other rendering alternatives and texture mapping facilities.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Some also contain features that support or allow animation of models.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Some may be able to generate full-motion video of a series of rendered scenes (i.e. animation).
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Computer-aided design software may employ the same fundamental 3-D modeling techniques that 3-D modeling software uses but their goal differs.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] They are used in computer-aided engineering, computer-aided manufacturing, Finite element analysis, product lifecycle management, 3D printing and computer-aided architectural design.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] After producing a video, studios then edit or composite the video using programs such as Adobe Premiere Pro or Final Cut Pro at the mid-level, or Autodesk Combustion, Digital Fusion, Shake at the high-end.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Match moving software is commonly used to match live video with computer-generated video, keeping the two in sync as the camera moves.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Use of real-time computer graphics engines to create a cinematic production is called machinima.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Not all computer graphics that appear 3D are based on a wireframe model.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics with 3D photorealistic effects are often achieved without wire-frame modeling and are sometimes indistinguishable in the final form.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Some graphic art software includes filters that can be applied to 2D vector graphics or 2D raster graphics on transparent layers.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Visual artists may also copy or visualize 3D effects and manually render photo-realistic effects without the use of filters.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Some video games use 2.5D graphics, involving restricted projections of three-dimensional environments, such as isometric graphics or virtual cameras with fixed angles, either as a way to improve performance of the game engine or for stylistic and gameplay concerns.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] By contrast, games using 3D computer graphics without such restrictions are said to use true 3D.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Cutout is the use of flat materials such as paper.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Everything is cut out of paper including the environment, characters, and even some props.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Silhouette is similar to cutouts except they are one solid color, black.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Puppets are dolls and different puppets used in the game.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] An example of this would be Yoshi's Wooly World.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] Pixelation is when the entire game appears pixelated, this includes the characters and the environment around them.
[src:babylonjs/3d-computer-graphics] One example of this is seen in Shovel Knight.
[src:babylonjs/babylon-js] It was initially released in 2013 under Microsoft Public License, having been developed by two Microsoft employees in their free time as a side-project.
[src:babylonjs/babylon-js] David Catuhe created the 3D game engine, while David Rousset implemented VR, Gamepad and IndexedDB support.
[src:babylonjs/babylon-js] The two were aided by artist Michel Rousseau, who contributed several 3D scenes.
[src:babylonjs/babylon-js] Babylon.js is based on an earlier game engine for Silverlight's WPF based 3D system.
[src:babylonjs/babylon-js] Catuhe's side-project then became his full-time job, and his team's primary focus.
[src:babylonjs/babylon-js] In 2015, it was presented at the WebGL Conference in Paris.
[src:babylonjs/babylon-js] Following its promotion and application in games, video game publisher Ubisoft released an Assassin's Creed title built atop the library in 2014.
[src:babylonjs/babylon-js] As of 2024, the project has more than 500 contributors.
[src:babylonjs/babylon-js] On 27 March 2025, Babylon.js 8.0 is released.
[src:babylonjs/babylon-js] The source code is written in TypeScript and then compiled into a JavaScript version.
[src:babylonjs/babylon-js] The JavaScript version is available to end users via NPM or CDN who then code their projects in JavaScript accessing the engine's API.
[src:babylonjs/babylon-js] The Babylon.js 3D engine and user code is natively interpreted by web browsers supporting the HTML5 standard and WebGL to undertake the 3D rendering.
[src:babylonjs/babylon-js] The 3D modeling process used is that of polygon modeling with triangular faces to be represented by shell models.
[src:babylonjs/babylon-js] Limited use of constructive solid geometry is possible, though only as a transitional method to create the union, subtraction, and intersection of shell models.
[src:babylonjs/babylon-js] The technique used to produce photo realistic images is that of physically based rendering along with post-processing methods.
[src:babylonjs/babylon-js] In order to simulate collisions between models and other real world physical actions, one of two physics engines need to be added as plugins: Cannon.js and Oimo.
[src:babylonjs/babylon-js] Animation involving, for example, changes in position or color of models is accomplished by key frame animation objects called "animatables," while full character animation is achieved through the use of skeletons with blend weights.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:babylonjs/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:babylonjs/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:babylonjs/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:babylonjs/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Here is an example of JavaScript syntax.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:babylonjs/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:babylonjs/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:babylonjs/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:babylonjs/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:babylonjs/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:babylonjs/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The main goal of WebAssembly is to facilitate high-performance applications on web pages, but it is also designed to be usable in non-web environments.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] It is an open standard intended to support any language on any operating system, and in practice many of the most popular languages already have at least some level of support.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Announced in 2015 (2015) and first released in March 2017 (2017-03), WebAssembly became a World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) recommendation on 5 December 2019 and it received the *Programming Languages Software Award* from the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The W3C maintains the standard with contributions from Mozilla, Microsoft, Google, Apple, Fastly, Intel, and Red Hat.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The name "WebAssembly" is intended to suggest bringing assembly language programming to the World Wide Web, where it will be executed client-side, by the website-user's computer via the user's web browser.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] To accomplish this, WebAssembly must be much more hardware-independent than a true assembly language.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] WebAssembly was first announced in 2015, and the first demonstration was executing Unity's *Angry Bots* in Firefox, Google Chrome, and Microsoft Edge [Legacy].
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The precursor technologies were asm.js from Mozilla and Google Native Client, and the initial implementation was based on the feature set of asm.js.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] In March 2017, the design of the minimum viable product (MVP) was declared to be finished and the preview phase ended.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] In late September 2017, Safari 11 was released with support.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] In February 2018, the WebAssembly Working Group published three public working drafts for the Core Specification, JavaScript Interface, and Web API.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The MVP was focused on low-level languages such as C and C++, with the intent to add features useful for high-level languages in a future version.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The WebAssembly 2.0 specification was finished in 2022 and became a W3C standard in December 2024.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] It adds many single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) related instructions and a new v128 datatype, with the ability for functions to return multiple values, mass memory initialize/copy instructions, and reference types, which are opaque pointers to objects outside of the linear memory.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] WebAssembly 3.0 was released in September 2025.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] New features include a 64-bit address space, multiple address spaces, exception handling, and garbage collected struct and array types.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Support for garbage collection enables more efficient compiling for high-level languages, but WasmGC from WebAssembly 3.0 lacks the abilities needed by .NET runtime.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] While WebAssembly was initially designed to permit near-native code execution speed in the web browser, it has been considered valuable outside of such, in more generalized contexts.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] A WebAssembly runtime environment is a low-level virtual stack machine, akin to JVM or Flash VM; it can be embedded into any host application, and thus there have been created standalone WebAssembly runtime environments, including Wasmtime , WebAssembly Micro Runtime , Wasmer , WasmEdge and wazero .
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] In November 2017, Mozilla declared support "in all major browsers", after WebAssembly was enabled by default in Edge [Legacy] 16.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] This support also includes mobile web browsers for iOS and Android.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] As of March 2024, 99% of tracked web browsers support WebAssembly (version 1.0), more than for its predecessor asm.js.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] For some extensions, from the 2.0 draft standard, support may be lower, but still more than 90% of web browsers may already support, e.g. the reference types extension.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Non-browser WebAssembly runtimes include Wasmer, Wasmtime, WAMR, WAVM, wasm3, and others.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] These systems execute precompiled Wasm modules and often provide additional APIs for embedding WebAssembly in different environments.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Use cases for wasm outside the browser include plug-in interfaces and lightweight virtualization.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] WebAssembly implementations generally use either ahead-of-time (AOT) or just-in-time (JIT) compiling, though some may also use an interpreter.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] While the first implementations appeared in web browsers, there are now many non-browser implementations for general-purpose use.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Because WebAssembly executables are precompiled, a variety of programming languages can target Wasm.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Compiling is done either through direct output to Wasm or via intermediate virtual machines implemented in Wasm.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] As of 2021, around 40 programming languages support WebAssembly as a compiling target.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Web browsers prevent WebAssembly code from directly manipulating the Document Object Model.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Wasm code must defer to JavaScript for this.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] In an October 2023 survey of developers, less than half of the 303 participants were satisfied with the state of WebAssembly.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] A large majority cited the need for improvement in four areas: § WASI, debugging support, integration with JavaScript and browser APIs, and build tooling.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] All major browsers allow WebAssembly if `Content-Security-Policy` is not specified, or if the value `unsafe-eval` is used, but behave differently otherwise; Chrome *requires* `unsafe-eval`, though a worker thread can be a workaround.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] In June 2018, a security researcher presented the possibility of using WebAssembly to circumvent browser mitigations for Spectre and Meltdown security vulnerabilities once support for threads with shared memory is added.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Due to this concern, WebAssembly developers put the feature on hold.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] However, in order to explore these future language extensions, Google Chrome added experimental support for the WebAssembly thread proposal in October 2018.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] WebAssembly has been criticized for allowing greater ease of hiding the evidence for malware writers, scammers and phishing attackers; WebAssembly is present on the user's machine only in its compiled form, which "[makes malware] detection difficult".
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Speed and the easy ability to conceal in WebAssembly have led to its use in hidden crypto mining within the website visitor's device.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] An April 2021 study from Universität Stuttgart found that since then crypto mining has been marginalized, falling to below 1% of all WebAssembly modules gathered from a wide range of sources, also including the Alexa top 1 million websites.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] As WebAssembly supports only structured control flow, it is amenable toward security verification techniques including symbolic execution.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] In 2019, a group of researchers from the University of Massachusetts Amherst presented a comprehensive analysis of WebAssembly's performance compared to native code.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The paper identified several reasons for this performance difference, including missing optimizations, code generation issues in WebAssembly compilers, and inherent limits of the WebAssembly platform.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] In 2022, it was determined by researchers that a Wasm program runs at about 120% of (or 20% faster than) the speed of a comparable JavaScript program.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Those findings align with the experience of a startup company named "Zaplib", whose founders summarized in a blog that it was shutting down due to lack of performance in WebAssembly.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Their goal had been to significantly increase the performance of existing web apps by incrementally porting them to Rust/Wasm; however, porting a customer's simulator from JavaScript yielded only a 5% improvement in performance.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Benchmarking has revealed several other pain-points for WebAssembly, such as poor performance because of no direct access to the DOM, a problem which is being addressed.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] WebAssembly System Interface (WASI) is a simple interface (application binary interface (ABI) and application programming interface (API)) designed by Mozilla, which is intended to be portable to any platform.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] It provides features similar to the Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX), such as file input/output (I/O) constrained by capability-based security.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] WASI is influenced by CloudABI and Capsicum.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Solomon Hykes, a co-founder of Docker, wrote in 2019, "If WASM+WASI existed in 2008, we wouldn't have needed to create Docker.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] WASI 0.1 provides a few POSIX-like APIs such as file I/O, reading environment variables, and random-number generation, but has very little support for networking.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] WASI 0.2 is redesigned based on the WebAssembly Component Model.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] WASI 0.3 will add support for async functions; the host translates between blocking and async function calls, so an exported function that blocks may be called as an asynchronous function, and vice-versa.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Starting in 0.2, WASI is defined in terms of the component model.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Interfaces in the component model are specified in an IDL called WIT (WebAssembly Interface Types).
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] While core wasm only supports integer and floating-point numbers, interfaces in WIT can express types such as strings, lists, and user-defined record and variant types, and are language-agnostic.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Components cannot access each other's memory, and so interact only via imported and exported functions.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The component model is designed around composition: two components can be composed into a single component when the exports of one component match another's imports, allowing any interface to be virtualized.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Interfaces in WIT are grouped together into a "world".
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] WASI 0.2 defines a CLI world similar to the POSIX-like API of WASI 0.1, and an HTTP proxy world for web servers.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The component model is not currently supported by browsers.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The general standard provides core specifications for the JavaScript API and details on embedding.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Wasm code (binary code, i.e. bytecode) is intended to be run on a portable virtual stack machine (VM).
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The VM is designed to be faster to parse and execute than JavaScript and to have compact code representation.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Any external functionality (like syscalls) that may be expected by Wasm binary code is not stipulated by the standard; instead, the standard specifies how the host environment can provide such an interface via a "module".
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] A Wasm program is designed as a separate module containing collections of various Wasm-defined values and program type definitions.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] These are provided in either binary or textual format (see below) that have a common structure.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Such a module may provide a start function that is executed upon instantiation of a wasm binary.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The list of instruction types includes those for standard memory load/store, numeric, parametric, control flow, and Wasm-specific variables.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The number of opcodes used in the original standard (§ MVP) was a bit fewer than 200 of the 256 possible opcodes.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Subsequent versions of WebAssembly pushed the number of opcodes a bit over 200.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The WebAssembly SIMD proposal (for parallel processing) introduces an alternate opcode prefix (0xfd) for 128-bit wide SIMD instructions; the concatenation of the SIMD prefix, plus an opcode that is valid after the SIMD prefix, forms each SIMD opcode.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] These SIMD opcodes are both portable and intended to map directly to native instruction sets like x86-64 and ARM.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] In contrast, SIMD instructions are not directly supported by Java's JVM or .NET's CIL; however, both do have some APIs for parallel processing, which provide SIMD speedups.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] A newer set of "relaxed SIMD" instructions allow for a limited amount of implementation-defined behavior to improve performance.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] In March 2017, the WebAssembly Community Group reached consensus on the initial ("MVP") binary format, JavaScript API, and reference interpreter.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] It defines a WebAssembly binary format (`.wasm`), which is designed to be used by computers, not humans, and a text format that is human-readable (`.wat`), resembling a cross between S-expressions and traditional assembly languages.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The binary format is straightforward and designed to allow streaming compiling, so compiling can begin before the module is finished downloading, and to allow functions to be compiled in parallel.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] All integer constants are encoded using a space-efficient, variable-length LEB128 encoding.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The WebAssembly text format is more canonically written in a folded format using S-expressions.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] For instructions and expressions, this format is purely syntactic sugar and has no behavioral differences with the linear format.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] A module is implicitly generated by the compiler.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The function is referenced by an entry of the type table in the binary, hence a type section and the `type` emitted by the decompiler.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The compiler and decompiler can be accessed online.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Data in memory is stored in a large, growable array of bytes termed a *linear memory*.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Linear memory is separate from the wasm module's call stack and code and the engine's memory.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] This allows running wasm code in the same process as the JavaScript virtual machine it's embedded in without violating memory safety.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] A module contains a list of global variables separate from linear memory, which may be mutable or immutable.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Functions declare a list of local variables.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] A function's parameters are also local variables.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Instructions operate on a stack of values.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The stack layout is fixed (branches must push and pop the same number of operands), so wasm engines can compile the stack away, producing efficient machine code operations on registers, rather than managing a stack at runtime.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] A stack machine architecture was chosen as it can have higher code density than a register machine.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Unlike typical assembly languages, wasm only uses structured control flow similar to high-level programming languages.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The intentional lack of support for jump instructions makes it simple to validate and compile wasm code in a single pass, and makes it easier to read code disassembled into the text format.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Blocks are delimited with the `block`, `loop`, and `if`/`else` constructs.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Branch instructions contain a label that identifies the depth of a block it is nested in: `br 0` will branch to the block the instruction is contained in, `br 1` will branch to the block that block is contained in, and so on.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Branches to a `block` or `if` jump to the end of the block like a break statement, while branches to a `loop` jump back to the *beginning* of the loop, similar to a continue statement.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] The `br_table` instruction takes an input index and jumps to a target from a list of labels.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] A C-style switch statement can be expressed with a `br_table` inside a series of nested blocks.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Compilers targeting wasm convert unstructured control flow into high-level loops using Emscripten's Relooper algorithm, originally designed to target JavaScript.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Function declarations are listed in a separate section before the section containing the function bodies.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Function pointers are emulated using an index into the global functions table, since code is not inside the linear memory.
[src:babylonjs/webassembly] Functions can also be imported and exported, providing the foreign function interface to communicate with JavaScript or other embedders.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] WebGL programs consist of control code written in JavaScript, and shader code written in OpenGL ES Shading Language (GLSL ES, sometimes referred to as ESSL), a language similar to C or C++.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] WebGL code is executed on a computer's GPU.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] WebGL is designed and maintained by the non-profit Khronos Group.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] On February 9, 2022, Khronos Group announced WebGL 2.0 support from all major browsers.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] From 2024, a new graphics API, WebGPU, is being developed to supersede WebGL.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] WebGPU provides extended capabilities, a more modern interface, and direct GPU access, which is useful for demanding graphics as well as AI applications.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] WebGL 1.0 is based on OpenGL ES 2.0 and provides an API for 3D graphics.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] It uses the HTML5 canvas element and is accessed using Document Object Model (DOM) interfaces.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] It guarantees the availability of many optional extensions of WebGL 1.0, and exposes new APIs.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] Automatic memory management is provided implicitly by JavaScript.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] Like OpenGL ES 2.0, WebGL lacks the fixed-function APIs introduced in OpenGL 1.0 and deprecated in OpenGL 3.0.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] This functionality, if required, has to be implemented by the developer using shader code and JavaScript.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] Shaders in WebGL are written in GLSL and passed to the WebGL API as text strings.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] The WebGL implementation compiles these strings to GPU code.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] This code is executed for each vertex sent through the API and for each pixel rasterized to the screen.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] WebGL evolved out of the Canvas 3D experiments started by Vladimir Vukićević at Mozilla.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] Vukićević first demonstrated a Canvas 3D prototype in 2006.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] By the end of 2007, both Mozilla and Opera had made their own separate implementations.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] In early 2009, the non-profit technology consortium Khronos Group started the WebGL Working Group, with initial participation from Apple, Google, Mozilla, Opera, and others.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] Version 1.0 of the WebGL specification was released March 2011.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] An early application of WebGL was Zygote Body.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] In November 2012 Autodesk announced that they ported most of their applications to the cloud running on local WebGL clients.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] These applications included Autodesk Fusion and AutoCAD.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] Development of the WebGL 2 specification started in 2013 and finished in January 2017.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] The specification is based on OpenGL ES 3.0.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] First implementations are in Firefox 51, Chrome 56 and Opera 43.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] Almost Native Graphics Layer Engine (ANGLE) is an open source graphic engine which implements WebGL 1.0 (2.0 which closely conforms to ES 3.0) and OpenGL ES 2.0 and 3.0 standards.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] It is a default backend for both Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox on Windows platforms and works by translating WebGL and OpenGL calls to available platform-specific APIs.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] WebGL is widely supported by modern browsers.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] However, its availability depends on other factors, too, like whether the GPU supports it.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] The official WebGL website offers a simple test page.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] More detailed information (like what renderer the browser uses, and what extensions are available) can be found at third-party websites.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] Some such libraries were ported to JavaScript from other languages.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] Examples of libraries that provide high-level features include A-Frame (VR), BabylonJS, PlayCanvas, three.js, OSG.JS, Google’s model-viewer and CopperLicht.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] Web3D also made a project called X3DOM to make X3D and VRML content run on WebGL.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] There has been an emergence of 2D and 3D game engines for WebGL, such as Unreal Engine 4 and Unity.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] The Stage3D/Flash-based Away3D high-level library also has a port to WebGL via TypeScript.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] A more light-weight utility library that provides just the vector and matrix math utilities for shaders is sylvester.js.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] It is sometimes used in conjunction with a WebGL specific extension called glUtils.js.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] There are also some 2D libraries built atop WebGL, like Cocos2d-x or Pixi.js, which were implemented this way for performance reasons in a move that parallels what happened with the Starling Framework over Stage3D in the Flash world.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] The WebGL-based 2D libraries fall back to HTML5 canvas when WebGL is not available.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] Removing the rendering bottleneck by giving almost direct access to the GPU has exposed performance limitations in the JavaScript implementations.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] Some were addressed by asm.js and WebAssembly (similarly, the introduction of Stage3D exposed performance problems within ActionScript, which were addressed by projects like CrossBridge).
[src:babylonjs/webgl] As with any other graphics API, creating content for WebGL scenes requires using a 3D content creation tool and exporting the scene to a format that is readable by the viewer or helper library.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] Desktop 3D authoring software such as Blender, Autodesk Maya or SimLab Composer can be used for this purpose.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] In particular, Blend4Web allows a WebGL scene to be authored entirely in Blender and exported to a browser with a single click, even as a standalone web page.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] There are also some WebGL-specific software such as CopperCube and the online WebGL-based editor Clara.io.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] Online platforms such as Sketchfab and Clara.io allow users to directly upload their 3D models and display them using a hosted WebGL viewer.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] Starting from Firefox Version 27, Mozilla has given Firefox built-in WebGL tools that allow the editing of vertices and fragment shaders.
[src:babylonjs/webgl] A number of other debugging and profiling tools have also emerged.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] In JavaScript, WebGPU can be provided by a web browser or other JavaScript environment like Node.js and Deno.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] Rust and C++ can use their respective implementations of the WebGPU specification.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] Other languages like Python, Java, and Go can use WebGPU by extending the C language specification.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] Google Chrome and Microsoft Edge first released WebGPU support in April 2023.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] Safari debuted WebGPU support in June 2025 with Safari 26.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] Firefox first released WebGPU in July 2025 with Firefox 141.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] The W3C standard is a candidate recommendation.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] WebGPU enables 3D graphics within an HTML canvas.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] It also has robust support for general-purpose GPU computations.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] WebGPU uses its own shading language called WebGPU Shading Language (WGSL) that was designed to be trivially translatable to SPIR-V, until complaints caused redirection into a more traditional design, similar to other shading languages.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] Tint is a Google-made compiler for WGSL.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] Naga is a similar project developed for the needs of wgpu-rs.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] Both Google Chrome and Firefox support WebGPU and WGSL.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] Firefox and Deno use the Rust wgpu library.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] Safari follows upstream specifications of both WebGPU and WGSL.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] Chrome version 113 enabled initial WebGPU support on Windows devices with Direct3D 12, ChromeOS devices with Vulkan, and macOS with Metal.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] This support for Android was enabled in version 121.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] On June 8, 2016, Google showed "Explicit web graphics API" presentation to the WebGL working group (during the bi-annual face to face meeting).
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] The presentation explored the basic ideas and principles of building a new API to eventually replace WebGL, aka "WebGL Next".
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] On January 24, 2017, Khronos hosted an IP-free meeting dedicated to discussion of "WebGL Next" ideas, collided with WebGL working group meeting in Vancouver.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] Google team presented the NXT prototype implementing a new API that could run in Chromium with OpenGL, or standalone with OpenGL and Metal.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] NXT borrowed concepts from all of Vulkan, Direct3D 12, and Metal native APIs.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] Apple and Mozilla representatives also showed their prototypes built on Safari and Servo correspondingly, both of which closely replicated the Metal API.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] On February 7, 2017, Apple's WebKit team proposed the creation of the W3C community group to design the API.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] At the same time they announced a technical proof of concept and proposal under the name "WebGPU", based on concepts in Apple's Metal.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] The WebGPU name was later adopted by the community group as a working name for the future standard rather than just Apple's initial proposal.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] The initial proposal has been renamed to "WebMetal" to avoid further confusion.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] The W3C "GPU for the Web" Community Group was launched on February 16, 2017.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] At this time, all of Apple, Google, and Mozilla had experiments in the area, but only Apple's proposal was officially submitted to the "gpuweb-proposals" repository.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] Shortly after, on March 21, 2017, Mozilla submitted a proposal for WebGL Next within Khronos repository, based on the Vulkan design.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] On June 1, 2018, citing "resolution on most-high level issues" in the cross-browser standardization effort, Google's Chrome team announced intent to implement the future WebGPU standard.
[src:babylonjs/webgpu] On 13 February, 2020, Google unveiled Tint as an alternative to WHLSL textual language proposal to WebGPU API, and the language eventually became the standardized WebGPU Shading Language (WGSL), and Tint became the name of compiler within Dawn, the WebGPU implementation of Chromium.
